<subSubSection id="55D970BF355EFFDD833DB97DFC1F5507" pageId="1" pageNumber="760" type="description">
<paragraph id="1D7C2334355EFFDD833DB97DFC1F5507" blockId="1.[811,1452,861,1557]" pageId="1" pageNumber="760">
The 
<taxonomicName id="DAC358B7355EFFDD8370B97EFBDC5067" authorityName="Mayr" authorityYear="1868" box="[864,1147,862,885]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Crematogaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ransonneti">
<emphasis id="2FB7FF26355EFFDD8370B97EFBDC5067" box="[864,1147,862,885]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="760">Crematogaster ransonneti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group can be distinguished from other Asian 
<taxonomicName id="DAC358B7355EFFDD83E3B95EFB4D5087" box="[1011,1258,893,917]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Crematogaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="2FB7FF26355EFFDD83E3B95EFB345087" box="[1011,1171,894,917]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="760">Crematogaster</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
by the following characters: (1) mandible with four teeth; (2) three-segmented antennal club; (3) deep metanotal groove; (4) propodeal spine well-developed and long (PSL 0.21–0.63); (5) propodeal spine directed posterolaterally in dorsal view; (6) petiole diamond-shaped and broadest at mid-length; (7) petiole distinctly wider than postpetiole (WI 73–92); and (8) postpetiole weakly globule but without distinct longitudinal median sulcus. This species group is similar to the 
<taxonomicName id="DAC358B7355EFFDD8346BEBEFC7257A7" authorityName="Forel" authorityYear="1911" box="[854,981,1181,1205]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Crematogaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fraxatrix">
<emphasis id="2FB7FF26355EFFDD8346BEBEFC7257A7" box="[854,981,1181,1205]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="760">C. fraxatrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group in having a diamond-shaped petiole (
<bibRefCitation id="79525EC5355EFFDD8324BE9DFBEE57C7" author="Hosoishi S &amp; Ogata K" box="[820,1097,1213,1237]" pageId="1" pageNumber="760" pagination="57 - 68" refId="ref4924" refString="Hosoishi S &amp; Ogata K (2014) Description and DNA barcoding of Crematogaster fraxatrix Forel, 1911 and two new closely related species from Cambodia and Indonesia (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). ZooKeys, 374: 57 - 68." type="journal article" year="2014">Hosoishi &amp; Ogata, 2014</bibRefCitation>
), but can be distinguished from the latter by the aforementioned characters (3), (4), and (5). Using a comprehensive molecular phylogeny, 
<bibRefCitation id="79525EC5355EFFDD8546BEDDFC245627" author="Blaimer BB" pageId="1" pageNumber="760" pagination="421 - 436" refId="ref4506" refString="Blaimer BB (2012 b) Acrobat ants go global - origin, evolution and systematics of the genus Crematogaster (Hymenoptera: Formicidae). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 65: 421 - 436." type="journal article" year="2012">Blaimer (2012b)</bibRefCitation>
revealed a sister relationship between 
<taxonomicName id="DAC358B7355EFFDD853DBF3EFA0C5627" authorityName="Forel" authorityYear="1911" box="[1325,1451,1309,1333]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Crematogaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fraxatrix">
<emphasis id="2FB7FF26355EFFDD853DBF3EFA0C5627" box="[1325,1451,1309,1333]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="760">C. fraxatrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="DAC358B7355EFFDD8349BF1EFC605647" authorityName="Emery" authorityYear="1888" box="[857,967,1341,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Crematogaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferrarii">
<emphasis id="2FB7FF26355EFFDD8349BF1EFC605647" box="[857,967,1341,1365]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="760">C. ferrarii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(as 
<taxonomicName id="DAC358B7355EFFDD83E2BF1EFB275647" authorityName="Emery" authorityYear="1888" box="[1010,1152,1341,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Crematogaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferrarii">
<emphasis id="2FB7FF26355EFFDD83E2BF1EFBAD5647" box="[1010,1034,1342,1365]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="760">C.</emphasis>
cf. 
<emphasis id="2FB7FF26355EFFDD8421BF1DFB275647" box="[1073,1152,1341,1365]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="760">ferrarii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The phylogenetic position of the 
<taxonomicName id="DAC358B7355EFFDD8368BF7EFBA95667" authorityName="Mayr" authorityYear="1868" box="[888,1038,1374,1397]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Crematogaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ransonneti">
<emphasis id="2FB7FF26355EFFDD8368BF7EFBA95667" box="[888,1038,1374,1397]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="760">C. ransonneti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group is currently unknown because fresh material of the group was unavailable for me. In the future, molecular phylogenetic analysis using fresh material will help verify the relatedness of the 
<taxonomicName id="DAC358B7355EFFDD84C1BF9EFAC356C7" authorityName="Mayr" authorityYear="1868" box="[1233,1380,1470,1493]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Crematogaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="760" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ransonneti">
<emphasis id="2FB7FF26355EFFDD84C1BF9EFAC356C7" box="[1233,1380,1470,1493]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="760">C. ransonneti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group with other species, which is currently inferred mostly from morphology.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="55D970BF355EFFDD833DBC1DFAA85487" pageId="1" pageNumber="760" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="1D7C2334355EFFDD833DBC1DFBE85587" blockId="1.[813,1453,1597,1685]" pageId="1" pageNumber="760">
This species group is distributed throughout parts of South and Southeast Asia (
<figureCitation id="85F83FB1355EFFDD841ABC7DFBEF5567" box="[1034,1096,1629,1653]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[136,171,1186,1208]" captionTargetBox="[137,1475,188,1170]" captionTargetId="figure-323@2.[134,1479,184,1174]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Distribution map of Crematogaster cornuta, C. keris, and C. ransonneti. Open circle = C. cornuta; open square = C. keris; open triangle = C. ransonneti." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5350240" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5350240/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="760">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), but has not been recorded from the Indochinese Peninsula.
</paragraph>
